
1. Acceptance Criteria

- User should be able to enter Full Name, Email, Current Address, and Permanent Address.
- Email should be required.
- Email should only accept a valid format.
- Current Address and Permanent Address should be optional.
- User should be able to click Submit successfully.
- After clicking Submit, the entered information should be shown correctly in the results section below.
- Submitted values should match exactly what the user entered.
- The page should remain stable even if long text is entered in any field.

2. Test Cases

Positive Scenarios
1. Submit the form with all fields filled with valid data.
2. Submit the form with only the required field (valid Email) and leave optional fields empty.
3. Verify submited data is displayed correctly after clicking Submit.

Negative Scenarios
4. Try submitting the form with Email empty.
5. Try submitting the form with an invalid email format.
6. Enter very long text in Full Name and verify the UI does not break.
7. Enter very long text in Current Address and Permanent Address and verify the UI still behaves correctly.

Basic Validation Scenarios
8. Verify the Submit button stays enabled at all times.
9. Verify invalid email is not accepted even though no validation message is shown.
10. Verify optional fields can be left blank.
11. Verify output values match the exact input entered by the user.

3. Risks / Edge Cases

- Full Name has no max length, so long values may overflow or break the layout.
- Address fields also have no character limit, which could cause UI or formating issues.
- Email validation is weak from a UX perspective, because there is no clear error message telling the user the format is invalid.
- Submit button is always enabled, which may confuse users when invalid data is entered.
- Special characters or large inputs may affect how data is displayed in the output section.
- Empty optional fields should still be handled correctly without causing display issues.
